          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In production environments, optical character recognition (OCR) is a critical component for automating document workflows, from invoice processing to identity verification. Teams face challenges in balancing accuracy, latency, and cost, especially when scaling to handle thousands of requests per minute. General-purpose models like OpenAI's multimodal APIs offer broad capabilities, but they may not be optimized for specific OCR tasks, leading to higher overhead and variable performance."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Nanonets OCR S is a specialized model designed for high-throughput, document-centric OCR, fine-tuned on datasets like invoices, receipts, and forms. Compared to OpenAI's offerings, it focuses on text extraction with lower latency and predictable pricing, making it a strong candidate for production APIs where reliability is paramount. This post breaks down the key differences, providing concrete data on performance, integration, and cost to help you decide which tool fits your stack."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "We'll cover capabilities, API integration, performance benchmarks, cost analysis, a real-world use case, deployment notes, and limitations. By the end, you'll have a clear framework for evaluating Nanonets OCR S against OpenAI in your context."
          }
        ]
      },
